Cell["\<\
The messengers of the Incas trekked through the Andes and into the coastal \
regions, carrying along sets of colored cords with knots known as quipu.  The \
Incas controlled a vast region in South America and used quipu to keep track \
of the economic resources of the empire. The renowned magnificent cities and \
fortresses, predominantly built on highlands and on the steep slopes of the \
Andes Mountains, contained a sophisticated road system that bridged the \
various regions of their empire for the purpose of transporting goods and \
information. Roads paved in flat stone were the foundational fabric atop \
which products and ideas essential for human advancement were transported.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76843866553588*^9, 3.768438732692091*^9}, {
   3.7685972649813337`*^9, 3.7685972911029844`*^9}, {3.768597334238487*^9, 
   3.768597342178536*^9}, {3.768597474399184*^9, 3.7685976403719497`*^9}, {
   3.7685977905027623`*^9, 3.768597805393881*^9}, 3.768599155033727*^9},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"ba2c5f61-5a62-4244-9916-0e3b2ec97cf0"],

Cell["\<\
\tThe versatility of the quipu recording system is remarkably impressive.  \
Knots were tied with varying numbers of loops to represent the digits from \
zero to nine, and the spacing of the knots indicated whether a particular \
knot represented 1\[CloseCurlyQuote]s, hundreds, thousands, and so on, making \
it possible to tie any number no matter how large. Think for a moment about \
the way different colored cords could be used to keep track of different \
commodities such as quinoa and alpacas. Using a system where strings can be \
tied onto other strings, one might consider using a main string for each \
village, with additional strings tied onto the main string to signify the \
different resources that belonged to that same village. Quipu were made of \
material readily available in a culture with well developed textiles and \
dyes, and they were easily transported from village to village.  \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76843866553588*^9, 3.76843875332034*^9}, {
  3.7685976499628534`*^9, 3.768597721450199*^9}, {3.7685978328752794`*^9, 
  3.7685979858512335`*^9}, {3.768598022887719*^9, 3.768598043029233*^9}, {
  3.7685985333283644`*^9, 3.768598642868763*^9}, {3.7685992888289404`*^9, 
  3.768599319485551*^9}, {3.768599824213252*^9, 3.7685998249208655`*^9}, {
  3.7685998628727283`*^9, 3.7685999029437857`*^9}},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"79f9f447-3f36-494f-8369-88017d2e9424"],

Cell["\<\
\tToday the code of the quipu is somewhat of a mystery, leaving the \
complicated structures' meanings up to our imagination and puzzlement. \
Exactly what was being enumerated or what a particular color or organization \
of strings represented is unknown today. What we do know is that this method \
of counting and enumeration was well developed and there are conventions \
consistent across all surviving quipu, indicating that several people in the \
culture shared a common understanding of how this ingenious system worked. \
Without understanding the system today, though, we are unable to benefit from \
the wealth of information contained in the remaining quipu.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76843866553588*^9, 3.7684387725334826`*^9}, {
   3.768598057152598*^9, 3.7685980755138392`*^9}, {3.7685981127595396`*^9, 
   3.7685981452899485`*^9}, {3.7685985065709343`*^9, 3.768598506854066*^9}, 
   3.768598656530754*^9, {3.7685999984538784`*^9, 3.768599999282871*^9}},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"3a4636c1-4494-48e8-ab4c-e521f20c5eed"],

Cell["\<\
\tNumerous ways of counting and organizing data have been developed \
throughout history. Every culture has had some means of quantifying their \
surroundings, and the systems that were developed reflect the priorities and \
lifestyles of the culture. Mathematics is a uniquely human creation that has \
skyrocketed our ability to understand, enumerate, and control our world. Some \
groups counted on their fingers, resulting in a base 10 system such as that \
used by the Incas. Using fingers and toes resulted in a base 20 system, such \
as that used by the Mayans and some of the Inuit. Counting on knuckles might \
lead to a base 8 system. Creating larger numbers often involved addition and \
multiplication of smaller numbers or using zero a place holder. What is \
important for each of these counting systems is that the members of the \
communities all agreed upon the same conventions and understood how the \
system worked.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76843866553588*^9, 3.768438769979721*^9}, {
  3.768438801569284*^9, 3.7684388053986654`*^9}, {3.7685981571081667`*^9, 
  3.768598178778675*^9}, {3.768598211656583*^9, 3.7685982808658185`*^9}},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"834d987b-2808-4197-995f-4d79ed60b34b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tIn mathematics,  agreed upon conventions are referred to as ",
 StyleBox["definitions or axioms",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". Properties of the resulting system are then expressed as ",
 StyleBox["lemmas ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "and ",
 StyleBox["theorems",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". The definitions that appear in textbooks have led to systems and theorems \
that are extremely valuable to present day people and are driving the \
technological revolution. In Chapter 0, matrices are introduced, which, like \
the quipu, can be used to record and preserve valuable information. There is \
a large amount of versatility in how to organize information. One very common \
method is to story it in a rectangular array.  Related data can be recorded \
across a row or down a column. Decisions about how data is recorded will \
depend on what types of information are important to glean from it.  ."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76843866553588*^9, 3.768438769979721*^9}, {
  3.7684388104178324`*^9, 3.7684388184355235`*^9}, {3.7685983089140787`*^9, 
  3.768598404007161*^9}, {3.768598774832366*^9, 3.7685989048143044`*^9}, {
  3.7685989670099883`*^9, 3.7685990570590315`*^9}, {3.7686001220877447`*^9, 
  3.7686002125494633`*^9}, {3.894532400688356*^9, 3.89453243164721*^9}, {
  3.9010211962618036`*^9, 3.9010211992373705`*^9}, {3.901021389865457*^9, 
  3.9010214251601133`*^9}, {3.9010214719736533`*^9, 3.901021653617074*^9}},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"07c9cce9-fcda-482d-9583-cbf405d06549"],

Cell["\<\
\tIn Chapter 2, we will begin to focus on ways to combine and process data.  \
A convention for multiplying two matrices together is the first step. The \
chosen definition will seem cumbersome, at first, and even counterintuitive, \
but as we move on through Chapter 2 and the rest of the textbook, we will see \
that this particular way of multiplying matrices was chosen for its \
usefulness in processing, transforming, and extracting information.  We will \
also develop properties of the mathematical system that results from our \
particular definition of multiplication and strategies that are useful when \
having computers calculate for us.  \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76843866553588*^9, 3.768438769979721*^9}, {
  3.7684388104178324`*^9, 3.7684388184355235`*^9}, {3.7685983089140787`*^9, 
  3.768598404007161*^9}, {3.768598774832366*^9, 3.7685989048143044`*^9}, {
  3.7685989670099883`*^9, 3.7685990570590315`*^9}, {3.7686001220877447`*^9, 
  3.7686002147232456`*^9}, {3.9010216695559835`*^9, 3.901021671242137*^9}, {
  3.9010217046065645`*^9, 3.9010217065088634`*^9}},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"36130bd5-6a2d-4154-ae32-f02c690324de"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Organizing Data Into Tables", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.5491129444842*^9, {3.5498229270653*^9, 3.5498229765172997`*^9}, {
   3.5498266720325003`*^9, 3.5498266829525003`*^9}, {3.6261800122418804`*^9, 
   3.626180022820551*^9}, 3.634745486945467*^9, {3.892577385587512*^9, 
   3.8925773934772563`*^9}, {3.89453262898466*^9, 3.894532637508027*^9}, {
   3.894634068264074*^9, 3.894634084687789*^9}},
 FontFamily->"Times New Roman",
 CellTags->
  "ORGANIZING DATA INTO \
TABLES",ExpressionUUID->"fa0c8f54-b12c-48c0-ac43-227c3840c250"],

Cell["\<\
In as early as Grade 1, students are introduced to the idea of working with \
data in tables.  In Example 1, a table listing the availablity of T-shirts at \
various store locations on the west coast of the United States is given.  In \
this example, the numbers are kept small so that hand calculations will be \
straight forward.  In this modern, data driven environment, understanding the \
processes applied to data is critical to understanding the output provided by \
various algorithms. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.5491129444842*^9, {3.5498229270653*^9, 3.5498229684053*^9}, {
   3.5498230024913*^9, 3.5498230125376997`*^9}, {3.5498230638461*^9, 
   3.5498231119565*^9}, {3.5498231586161003`*^9, 3.5498234013989*^9}, {
   3.5498234791649*^9, 3.5498234909741*^9}, {3.5498266346705*^9, 
   3.5498266353101*^9}, {3.5499779014230003`*^9, 3.5499779072530003`*^9}, {
   3.6261772267066236`*^9, 3.6261772267066236`*^9}, {3.6261773123754616`*^9, 
   3.6261773123754616`*^9}, {3.626177380614787*^9, 3.6261773886308126`*^9}, {
   3.626179735672755*^9, 3.6261797383262205`*^9}, {3.6261799996630917`*^9, 
   3.6261800033039036`*^9}, 3.627208991322288*^9, {3.633623755398562*^9, 
   3.633623757592882*^9}, {3.634743119271941*^9, 3.634743140715146*^9}, {
   3.634743176491867*^9, 3.634743184096486*^9}, {3.8925773980789633`*^9, 
   3.8925774196295156`*^9}, {3.892577840516201*^9, 3.8925778952104797`*^9}, {
   3.894532695734226*^9, 3.894532726726737*^9}, {3.8945343850640774`*^9, 
   3.894534405133507*^9}, 3.894627657308608*^9, {3.9010212627798986`*^9, 
   3.901021373109848*^9}, {3.9010217178484073`*^9, 3.90102185572849*^9}},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"00f5b6db-91d6-4652-8659-bf1c4d70e447"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["EXAMPLE 1", "ExampleFont"]], "Subsubsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.626704328978153*^9},
 FontFamily->"Times New Roman",
 CellTags->"EXAMPLE 1",ExpressionUUID->"7bb90381-0ca4-4fd8-b1bb-a51086234d11"],

Cell["TABLE 1:  T-shirt availability by color and location", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.5491129444842*^9, {3.5498229270653*^9, 3.5498229684053*^9}, {
   3.5498230024913*^9, 3.5498230125376997`*^9}, {3.5498230638461*^9, 
   3.5498231119565*^9}, {3.5498231586161003`*^9, 3.5498234013989*^9}, {
   3.5498234791649*^9, 3.5498234954825*^9}, {3.5505784270087*^9, 
   3.5505784506857*^9}, 3.5506718684487*^9, 3.626177550553909*^9, 
   3.8945319499898877`*^9, {3.8945424380150285`*^9, 3.8945424427754345`*^9}, 
   3.9010222379157395`*^9},
 FontFamily->
  "Times New Roman",ExpressionUUID->"2317d4af-4a49-48d3-8224-207d09adbd0c"],

Cell[TextData[Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[GridBox[{
    {GridBox[{
       {
        StyleBox[
         RowBox[{"Color", "/", "Location"}], "Text",
         FontWeight->"Plain"], "Seattle", "Portland", 
        RowBox[{"San", " ", "Franciso"}], 
        RowBox[{"Los", " ", "Angeles"}]},
       {"Black", "14", "12", "15", "17"},
       {"Grey", "15", "10", "12", "16"},
       {"Blue", "7", "6", "9", "20"},
       {"Crimson", "12", "8", "10", "12"},
       {"White", "7", "8", "3", "6"},
       {"Green", "9", "2", "7", "12"}
      },
      GridBoxDividers->{"Columns" -> {{True}}, "Rows" -> {{True}}}]}
   },
   GridBoxItemSize->{"Columns" -> {{
        Scaled[0.96]}}}], 
  TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"27914526-5de6-4d3d-beb8-973e6c0c7bad"]], \
"Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8945424575839148`*^9, 3.894542460618862*^9}, {
  3.89454253404348*^9, 3.894542645045879*^9}, {3.894542829692956*^9, 
  3.894542829692956*^9}, {3.8945428875492544`*^9, 3.894542902209154*^9}, {
  3.9010222467520437`*^9, 
  3.9010222467520437`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"75033bd0-d8cf-46ad-afc6-\
daed2d1a5e92"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Horizontal strips of the data are referred to as the ",
 StyleBox["rows ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "of the table and verticle strips are referred to as ",
 StyleBox["columns",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ".  Think about how information in the table might be combined.  For \
example, adding all the numbers in a particular row calculates the number of \
T-shirts available of a particular color.  In contrast, adding all the \
numbers in a particular column calculates the number of T-shirts at a \
particular location. More complicated questions can be asked about the data.  \
For example, how much it would cost, for each color, to ship all the T-shirts \
to Seattle given that the cost of shipping from Portland to Seattle is $1 per \
T-shirt, from San Francisco to Seattle is $2 per T-shirt and the cost of \
shipping from Los Angelese to Seattle is $3 per T-shirt?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8945426603681912`*^9, 3.8945429118129582`*^9}, {
   3.8945433514031982`*^9, 3.8945433530669527`*^9}, 3.894631867909255*^9, {
